50|$|This {{plant is}} {{sometimes}} substituted for {{other species of}} its genus which are used as herbal remedies, such as <b>American</b> <b>spikenard</b> and Japanese spikenard. A preparation of the root has traditionally been used as an anti-inflammatory, douche, and cough suppressant.|$|E
50|$|Aralia racemosa, {{with common}} names <b>American</b> <b>spikenard,</b> small spikenard, Indian root, spice berry, spignet, life-of-man, petty morel, is an {{ornamental}} {{plant in the}} Araliaceae family native to the United States and Canada. It is a herbaceous plant, about one to two meters tall, which grows in shady areas. Its native range includes most of the eastern United States.|$|E

